          "body": "The father positions himself as witness — at the window, through the lattice (7:6), looking down at the street below. The vantage point is theological as much as spatial: he can see what the young man cannot see about himself. What the father observes is the structure of the young man's failure before the woman speaks a word. He is among the 'naive' (peti, 7:7), he is 'lacking sense' (chaser lev, literally 'lacking heart'), and his feet have already carried him 'near her corner' and 'the way to her house' (7:8) — in the deep darkness of night (7:9). Three levels of vulnerability compound: social (naive, unformed), moral (no internalized wisdom-heart), and spatial (feet already on the wrong path in the wrong hour). The woman then appears — dressed for the role, cunning of heart (7:10), restless and predatory (7:11-12). She seizes and kisses him before speaking (7:13). Then comes the speech: she uses the language of fulfilled religious duty (peace offerings, paid vows, 7:14) to create an aura of divine sanction; she deploys luxury imagery (Egyptian linen, myrrh, aloes, cinnamon, 7:16-17) to overwhelm the senses; she removes the sense of consequence by announcing the husband's precisely-dated absence (7:19-20). The speech is a masterwork of manipulation — it addresses the young man's desire for significance ('I sought you earnestly,' 7:15), his senses (7:16-17), his appetite (7:18), and his fear (7:19-20). It is, as Derek Kidner observed, one of the most psychologically acute portrayals of seduction in ancient literature."
