          "body": "The narrative ends and the father speaks directly to his sons — now plural, widening the lesson (7:24). The imperative is not 'do not commit adultery' but something more fundamental: 'do not let your heart turn aside to her ways, do not stray into her paths' (7:25). The battle is located in the heart (lev) before it ever reaches the feet. This is the chapter's most practically decisive verse. Everything the father has described — the woman's dress, her speech, the luxury, the manufactured privacy — is aimed at bending the heart. The prescription is not vigilance about outward behavior alone but the internalized wisdom of verses 1-4 that keeps the heart from turning before the feet follow. Verses 26-27 close with the body count and the terminal geography. 'Many are the victims she has cast down, and numerous are all her slain' (7:26) — the young man of the story is not exceptional; he is typical. Her house is 'the way to Sheol, descending to the chambers of death' (7:27). The father does not soften the ending. The chapter that began with 'keep my commandments and live' (7:2) ends with the chambers of death as the destination of those who do not."
