          "title": "The adulteress as Dame Folly: the canonical frame",
          "body": "Proverbs 7 cannot be read in isolation from the architecture of Proverbs 1-9. The entire section is structured as two competing personifications: Lady Wisdom (Proverbs 1:20-33; chapter 8; 9:1-6) and Dame Folly (Proverbs 9:13-18), with the adulteress of chapters 5-7 serving as Folly's narrative embodiment. The father of Proverbs 7 is not simply warning against a specific category of sexual sin — he is using that sin as the paradigm case for all departure from wisdom. The adulteress's house as Sheol (7:27) corresponds to Folly's invitation in 9:18: 'he does not know that the dead are there, that her guests are in the depths of Sheol.' The structural parallel is deliberate. When chapter 8 opens with Lady Wisdom crying out in the very streets and corners where the adulteress lurked (8:1-3), the geography of chapter 7 is being redeemed: the same public spaces that are hunting grounds for Folly are platforms for Wisdom. The reader is invited into a choice that chapter 9 makes explicit: two women, two houses, two meals, two destinations. Proverbs 7 provides the full negative case so that chapter 8's positive case will be heard by ears that know what is at stake."
